details

public <T extends nl.flotsam.pecia.SimpleContents<?>> nl.flotsam.pecia.Documenter<T> details(String bufferReference)
Description copied from interface: CodecDescriptor
Returns an object capable of writing detailed information on the format to the document section passed in. Typically implemented by writing a (couple of) paragraph(s), and forwarding to the CodecDescriptor of a nested Codec. Note that - while forwarding - the descriptor has the option to replace the way the buffer is referenced.

Specified by:
details in interface CodecDescriptor
Parameters:
bufferReference - A String based human readable reference to the encoded data.

reference

public <T extends nl.flotsam.pecia.ParaContents<?>> nl.flotsam.pecia.Documenter<T> reference(CodecDescriptor.Adjective adjective,
                                                                                             boolean startWithCapital)
Description copied from interface: CodecDescriptor
Returns an object capable of rendering a short reference to the type of data for which the Codec provides the decoder. This reference should at least include a reference to the type of data decoded by 'sub'-Codecs. The CodecDescriptor.Adjective argument allows the implementor to generate a correct reference, such as 'a list' instead of 'an list'.

Note that implementers should assume that the particular piece of data that is going to be referenced here will be detailed further along the road. Unless CodecDescriptor.requiresDedicatedSection() returns true, that could be within the same section.

Specified by:
reference in interface CodecDescriptor
Parameters:
adjective - The adjective to use; null if no adjective should be used.
startWithCapital - TODO

summary

public <T extends nl.flotsam.pecia.ParaContents<?>> nl.flotsam.pecia.Documenter<T> summary()
Description copied from interface: CodecDescriptor
Returns an object capable of writing a one-line summary of the data structure. Expect the summary to be printed at the beginning of a paragraph, but make sure the paragraph is ended in such a way that more lines might be appended to that paragraph, if required, by some other component. I.e. make sure you end with a dot-space. (". ") Typically starts with CodecDescriptor.Adjective.A. Will often rely on #writeReference(ParaContents, Adjective) for its implementation.

Specified by:
summary in interface CodecDescriptor
